node.text:
Morning meds for a kitten with kidney disease ♥️

Ferguson is thriving on this medication routine, and the best part is that he actually enjoys it! I wanted to share this sped-up look at what meds and supplements he takes every morning (and also how he takes them) in case that is helpful or interesting to you.

I use Ferguson’s favorite treats to motivate him to participate in med time. As you can see, he knows the routine and actually looks forward to these sessions! There is no one right way to work with kittens who need this much medication, but my approach is to see what works best for him, to keep everything as positive as possible, and to make adjustments as needed.

Here is what you’re seeing in the video:
-Subcutaneous fluids (LRS) with a 25g butterfly needle
-Injectable famotidine (an antacid, commonly known as Pepcid) which can be given with fluids
-Azodyl (a probiotic supporting renal health) mixed with churu
-Porous One (a uremic toxin binder) mixed with churu
-Orbax (an antibiotic)
-Clavamox (an antibiotic)
-Aluminum hydroxide (a phosphorous binder)
-He also gets injectable Cerenia (an antiemetic) which I do during his PM meds, so you don’t see that here

Please remember every case is different and you are advised to meet with a veterinary nephrology specialist to determine the right treatment for your kitten or cat! All of the medication given in this video is given under the guidance of Ferguson’s veterinary team.

node.text:
Nothing could warm my heart more than watching Ferguson play with Spud & the Buds! Here is 4 minutes of sweet playtime footage taken just a few minutes ago.

Fergie is 12 weeks old, while Spud & the Buds are about 5 weeks old…but due to his size and fragility they match really nicely for playtime. Now that the little ones are all healthy and past a nice long quarantine period, I felt comfortable letting him interact with them, and as you can see he is loving every minute!

Sadly, Ferguson is showing some physical signs of late stage kidney failure. To be completely honest, I have cried about it a lot over the past 24 hours. But then I’ll walk in the room and see him playing like this—or see him eat a big breakfast (more than half a can today!) and the only thing I can feel is happiness and hope. In spite of all he’s going through, he has such spunk and such a strong will to live a joyful life. I admire that about him so much. ♥️

UPDATE: SHE FOUND A HOME!!! ♥️ Can we all come together and help this incredible senior gal?! Skyy is 20 years old(!) but doesn’t act a day over 10. She’s loving, affectionate, and impeccably fluffy. Skyy was well-loved for her entire life, but her human recently passed away and she ended up at the humane society. She so deserves a wonderful home to live out her golden years! Will you share her video & tag friends in Southern California who might be interested in her?

Skyy is adoptable from San Diego Humane Society. Let’s boost her story & help find her an amazing home! ♥️ @sdhumanesociety

Today we took in a new foster kitten! Spud is a tiny kitten the size & development of a 5-7 day old, but if you can believe this…he’s actually 16 days old! He was born very prematurely when his mama, a feral cat, came into our local TNR clinic @feral_cat_coalition in a trap. He was the only kitten born, and his mama was not able to care for him, so he was raised for the past two weeks by the clinic manager, @aud_everything_is_taken. Audrey reached out and asked if we had any interest in taking him on, and of course, we said HECK YES!

His former foster name was Bruno, but since we have already raised a baby Bruno, we collectively decided to name him after what he looks like most — a chonky potato. As you can see, he has an incredible appetite and a rotund belly! Audrey, you did a beautiful job getting him through his most vulnerable weeks, and I’m so happy we can help carry the baton from here to adoption.

Welcome, Spud Spudley! We love you!🥔

Today was spay/neuter day for Spud & The Buds…but Spud was the only one who made weight for his appointment! We spay and neuter our kittens once they have hit 2 pounds, but The Buds are juuuuust under that, so they were rescheduled for next week. Fortunately Spud is already out of his neuter surgery, and will be back home very soon!

Why do we spay/neuter at 2 pounds? So many reasons!
-pediatric surgeries are easier, faster, and have fewer complications
-anesthetic recovery and healing are faster in younger animals
-sterilizing prior to reaching sexual maturity eliminates the risk of pregnancy & decreases unwanted behaviors like spraying
-most importantly, spaying and neutering at 2 pounds allows kittens to transition out of rescues and into forever homes at a young age, which has many many benefits including decreased exposure to disease, increased bonding with adopters, and of course the rescue’s ability to save more kittens! 💖

I’ll pop some articles about pediatric spay/neuter into my IG stories today for people who are wanting to learn more. ✨

Happy Black Cat Appreciation Day! Do you have a black cat? Tell me something you appreciate about them! 🖤

While I do think things are starting to get better with black cat adoptions, I unfortunately still notice that our black kittens tend to get fewer applications than the others. This always saddens me deeply because they are truly the most lovely cats. I often hear people say “adopt with your heart, not your eyes,” but I don’t feel like that should even apply to this scenario, because…I mean…have you SEEN black cats?! They are gorgeous! Who wouldn’t want a sleek micropanther in their house?!

All of this is to say that my best friend is a black cat, and yours could be too. Next time you go to adopt, check out the black cats at your local rescues and shelter. And hey, if you live in Southern California, you could even adopt my foster kitten pictured here—DAISY GOLD!

In honor of #BlackCatAppreciationDay, here are some things I appreciate about Daisy Gold:

-She is so chatty and communicative! She has a variety of vocalizations including chirps and pops for toy hunting, “mlehhhhs” for attention and food, and squeaks for love.

-She loves other cats and will cuddle up with a sibling, a foster friend, or even a resident cat. She just loves feline company!

-She is drop dead gorgeous, with big eyes and silky fur.

-She is extremely playful and has mastered a number of different toys, including her current favorite, a circular ball chaser.

-She is always down to snuggle. Always!

Apply to adopt Daisy Gold and/or her siblings here: orphankittenclub.org/adopt 🖤

Things I love about Blue Bell ♥️

-She is so inquisitive and curious about the world around her. She loves to explore, and I never know where I’ll find her next!

-She’s extremely smart and wants to figure out new things, like how to use new toys or climb tall cat trees. When she sees something unfamiliar, she gazes at it with an adorable puppydog head-tilt! Sometimes I even hear her gently chirping to herself as she tries to troubleshoot a high jump. So cute.

-She’s bunny-soft and has a stunning supermodel face and precious pink jellybean toes.

-At just seven weeks old, she has already mastered the art of snuggling.

Blue Bell is looking for a home in Southern California! Her brother Ranger Russet and sister Daisy Gold are also available for adoption. You can learn more about all three of them, and apply to adopt, at orphankittenclub.org/adopt ♥️

Ferguson is 16 👏 WEEKS 👏 OLD! 👏

If this face doesn’t say “haha, I tricked you into thinking I had only a few days to live & then you adopted me because you felt bad & now I feel much better & you have to keep me & feed me treats forever LOL gotcha” then I don’t know what does!

At 16 weeks, Ferguson is weighing in around 2 lb 10 oz, which is about 70% of a target weight for his age. He’s a lil skinny guy but he has a good appetite and amazing energy. He delights and surprises me every day with his joyful, trusting nature, and it is so cute to see him developing little routines that show us he knows he is at home.

For those who have asked if he is still considered terminal, well, I’m honestly not sure how to answer that. He still has kidney disease, and still takes three medications and two supplements every day (and fluids.) But right now his health seems very manageable and his prognosis is not imminently poor. In a few weeks, he’ll have an ultrasound to see how his kidneys are doing visually. My hope is that we will be in for another pleasant surprise.

Renal health is something that usually focuses around seniors—less so babies. Very little is known about what is possible for kidneys that are still growing. My deepest hope is that as he grows, his kidneys will be able to grow some normal tissue and give him enough function to live a long life. A few weeks ago I wouldn’t have dared to dream so boldly, but now, I do. ♥️

A few years ago, I surveyed thousands of foster parents and asked them to share what they felt were the most frustrating or hurtful things people say to them. Unsurprisingly, there were a few themes that were commonly shared, and I found each and every one of them deeply relatable, myself.

I took the six most common responses, and turned them into DO & DON’T infographics to help people learn how to speak in a way that is supportive of foster parents. But for some reason, I never shared them!

The truth is that sometimes people don’t realize the impact their words have, or just don’t know what to say. I hope these graphics can give you some helpful ideas for speaking supportively!

So here you have it: six very common phrases that foster parents don’t like to hear, and six ways to rephrase them so that foster parents feel supported. ♥️

Photos by @iamthecatphotographer and me

Ferguson loves kittens. So why aren’t we bringing home new foster kittens for him right now?

Well, because Ferguson does not yet have adequate protection against viruses! Although we typically vaccinate kittens starting at 6 weeks of age, Ferguson’s vet recommended that we not vaccinate him while in the throes of kidney disease. We expected him to pass away weeks ago, and vaccination was not in the cards at the time. However, as he has gotten older & a little healthier, it has grown to be my biggest concern: will I ever be able to vaccinate this dang cat?!?

If you have a cat, you know that every cat should receive FVRCP vaccination. FVRCP stands for Feline Viral Rhinotracheitis, Calicivirus, and Panleukopenia. These are three potentially devastating illnesses, but cats can become well protected through vaccination. Sadly, Ferguson has had zero protection against these diseases.

Many viruses are highly transmissible from kitten-to-kitten, but it’s important to know that virsuses like panleukopenia can even be transmitted through environmental contact! That means it can enter your house on your hands, your shoes, your phone, etc. And the most at risk cats are kittens, sick cats, and unvaccinated cats. Ferguson is all three. 😔

Fortunately, I was given permission to vaccinate him yesterday! Yay! But it will take time for him to build antibodies. Until he does, it is best not to intake animals directly into our home without a quarantine period.

But, @orphankittenclub is a TEAM—and a pretty amazing one! Our incredible Program Director Sonja @me0wsages has volunteered to quarantine kittens until we are certain they don’t have transmissible viruses. So yesterday, we took in 7 new babies, and they are in Sonja’s care for the time being! I could not be more grateful for her help! They will come here in 2 weeks. 😍

Because they came in on Friday the 13th, we have given them horror names: Norman, Babadook, Wolfman, Carrie, Chucky, Candyman & Samara!

If there’s one thing rescue has taught me, it’s to be adaptive, flexible, and collaborative. I’m so grateful we can still help this 7-pack while also keeping Fergie safe, and I can’t wait to have them here in 2 weeks! ♥️

Poop, glorious poop! 💩 Who’s going to be joining me one week from today for my POOPINAR?

Next Saturday, I’m teaching a 90 minute @catcampusa virtual class all about The Scoop on Kitten Poop, along with the amazing Dr. Rachel Wallach @wee_vet! Join us at 10am PT on Saturday August 21st. Register now at catcamp.com 💩

Why do I care so much about kitten poop? Well, because it’s like I always say: Poop is a kitten’s report card. It prints straight out of their little bodies and tells you, “I’m doing great” or “I need a little assistance” or even “I’m having an emergency.” We want to be aiming for A+ poop for our little ones! If a kitten has a C for constipation or a D for diarrhea…you should care and you should intervene. Lucky for you, you can learn all the tools you need next week!

In the POOPINAR, we’ll cover everything from parasites to viruses, from stimulation techniques to fecal scalding, from diagnostic tools to lifesaving interventions. We’ll also do a long Q&A to answer all your poopy questions! If you’re a kitten foster parent, you need this talk. Trust me!

I want to thank @petagpetproducts for their generous support of this lecture. PetAg’s probiotic, Bene-Bac PLUS, is hands down my favorite probiotic on the market and has played a major role in the GI health of my kittens, especially Ferguson (seen here.) Ferguson has been antibiotic dependent for his entire life, and the inclusion of Bene-Bac PLUS in his health routine has truly made a tremendous difference for him. You can read my article about why I love this probiotic and how to use it at www.petag.com/education/probiotics-how-to-use-them-and-why

If Fergie had social media (or had any idea what social media was!) he would probably be horrified that I’m posting this baby photo of him, but he doesn’t, so here it is: his baby poop photo 🤗

So what say you, kitten foster parents? Will I see you there?! Register now at catcamp.com ♥️
